Compiler (see section 4.3). For the second, we measure by means of custom tools the characteristics of programs
at two abstraction levels: LLVM‚Äôs intermediate representation and Clang‚Äôs abstract syntax trees6 . We refer to both
as IR and AST respectively.
After preparing the data, we use the SVM as explained in section 3.2: (1) we divide the examples dataset into
the training set and the test set (respectively 80% and 20% of the initial set); (2) we train the SVM with the training
set; (3) we assess the quality of our model by computing the LOOCV accuracy and by plotting the learning curve.
To implement these experiments, we use libsvm7 , a stable and free library for SVM.
4.3. Our Baseline
We compare our results against two baselines. The Ô¨Årst one is Intel Compiler alone (see details below).
The second one is the exact same experiments as the ones described in section 4.2, but using nearest neighbor
(NN) instead of SVM. NN is a simple machine learning technique that considers for prediction the vectorization
proÔ¨Åtability of the closest training data with respect to the Euclidian distance in the space of features.
We compare against Intel compiler alone because it is considered by the community as one of the brightest
available vendor compiler. With respect to P1, it has a success rate of 56%. This number is the ratio of proÔ¨Åtable
vectorization among the examples dataset used in section 4.4; we consider all the kernels and all the unroll factors,
and Intel Compiler has unrolling, loop pipelining and loop vectorization oÔ¨Ä.
With respect to P2, it is impossible to reproduce Exp2 with Intel Compiler. Instead, we consider its success
ratio to proÔ¨Åtably generate SIMD instructions when it is possible. We consider the 151 non-unrolled programs, and
we activate unrolling in Intel Compiler (by removing the nounroll pragmas). By doing so, we ask Intel Compiler
to Ô¨Ågure out by itself a correct transformation to apply (including unrolling) in order to generate proÔ¨Åtable vectors.
It succeeds for 13 programs. However, as explained in section 4.4, it is possible to Ô¨Ånd an unroll factor that enables
proÔ¨Åtable vectorization for 63 programs. Therefore, its success rate is 20.63% (13/63).
4.4. Experimental Results
First of all, let us take a look at Ô¨Ågure 4 a. It plots the number of times that vectorization was proÔ¨Åtable for
each benchmark. This graph conÔ¨Årms that our data are not skewed. Further analyses show that the ratio of the
execution time without vectors and the same with vectors ranges from 0.46 to 39.25. In other words, ABBV may
provide up to 39.25 time speedups, but failing to recognize non-proÔ¨Åtable ABBV may slow down the compiled
program up to 2.2 times (0.46‚àí1 = 2.2). The latter occurs for the program s116 with an unroll factor of 2.
